Service: impeccable Food: excellent Why didn't I give it 5 stars? I think i was expecting more so I felt it was a bit overrated. Not that I didn't enjoy it...because I did. However after someone (or multiple someones) tell you it was the best meal they've ever had, you partly expect angels to be circling above your head throughout the meal. (granted there are servers circling around you during the entire meal which was pretty cool.) I had the 4 course meal with no cheese platter. Surprisingly the bread there was served cold. ( I expected warm bread) Amuse bouche was a curried cauliflower soup. It was excellent. My first course was the crispy fried egg with frisee salad over white corn polenta. The egg still amazes me. I have no idea how it was prepared--it was a panko crusted deep fried egg, but yet like a perfectly cooked poached egg inside.... It was divine. Not sure it needed polenta but it was good. Second course Maine lobster... Really really yummy. The only thing is the sauce had a really similar flavor to the soup earlier so it wasn't a new taste but still good. Third course: pork belly woth pork tenderloin with a fava bean purée. The pork belly had a maple glaze and was cooked perfectly. The tenderloin was excellent. It was a hearty portion. I couldnt finish the course because i was already full and still had dessert coming. One of my friends had the cheese plate and the presentation made me wish I did as well. It was wheeled out on a cart and the selection was amazing. One thing we all noted though is that the accoutrements for the cheese plate were not as impressive as the selection of cheeses. I had hoped for some higher end accompanying items instead of just some plain walnuts, some slices of baguette and some grapes. Finally dessert. I had the butter cake, which was really tasty, but it kind of reminded me of a sticky bun. So a little puzzling since i was expecting more of a pound cake type dessert. we were seated at a table where it seemed to be in some poor accoustics. I had a difficult time hearing my other dining companions. It is definitely a special occasion place, but some people were dressed like they were just walking in off the street on a whim. Come on people, you have to call in for a res like two months in advance, leave your t-shirt and jeans at home! Couple of cool random things as a female: If you get a little chilly, they have complementary pashminas you can use during the meal. Also, they have Gary Danko branded handbag hangers for you to hang your bag at the table. FUN! I'd come back again, and the price was much more reasonable than I had imagined.

This place is phenomenal! Quite simply, once of the best dinners I have ever had! Top notch service. We were celebrating my dear friend's birthday and decided to go here because we were eyeing this place for a long time. And boy, they did not disappoint! My friend got her favorite old-fashioned to start with and she says it's the best old-fashioned she had in a looong time. For dinner, we both chose the 4 course menu. Started off with Crab risotto & the Crispy farm egg with polenta. Both awesome, but I especially liked the Crispy farm egg. It's good to see they have hearty dishes. And the polenta it came on was sooo good; buttery, warm and delicious!! For the second course we both had to have the Roast lobster, which again was delicious. The third course was a disappointment, which they readily corrected. My beef fillet was just bland! I mean, it had NO flavor, felt like I was chewing on stale blubber. Surprising because everything leading up to it was so good. My waiter replaced it instantly with the Moroccan Lamb with couscous & dates- I tell you, this Lamb was out of the world! You definitely, definitely have to try this lamb! Super tender and the couscous and dates complemented it very very well! Finished off with the Baked chocolate soufflé and a warm Louisiana cake with ice cream. I have to say while the desserts were good, they weren't great. In my book, wouldn't even feature in the top 10 restaurants for desserts in SF (Absinthe being the absolute best). As I said service was topnotch! We had staff checking in on us throughout, without being overbearing. Exception being this one lady, who had such a fake smile and attitude, it was actually painful to interact with her when she came to our table. All in all, great atmosphere, amazing food and good service! Thank you for a great evening guys!!

The food was delicious, everything was sooo good. We got the tasting menu. The lobster salad is at the top of the list. Loved this place. Service was excellent. If ever in San Fran again, will definitely go back. I recommend this place to all my friends who go to San Fran.

Tracey and I got there at 6:30 so we could "walk in" and sit at the bar and it was already 3/4's of the way full. Within 10 minutes the bar was full and dining at the bar is not a quick meal nor do they rush the meal. They take reservations 2 months in advance from online, but I'm told there are sometimes cancellations so it's worth trying to put your name on the list. I started this amazing night, my first visit to Gary Danko with one of the best Manhattan's ever. Basil Hayden is always great and one of my favorites, but when the bartender knows how to make a great Manhattan it's golden. I'm picky about my drinks and truth be told, I generally do not order a Manhattan from a bartender that is under 40 years old. The drink was highly memorable and a great way to begin a very nice night. The way Gary Danko sets up his menu is very interesting and worth investigating more, very soon, I hope. One can go the 5 course prix fix route or the menu is filled with appetizer as well as entree sized portions, priced accordingly. You choose 3, 4, 5 course meal options built around your entree choice which can include soup, salad, small plate(s), dessert, cheese. Your third option or you can just dine normally and order what you want from the menu. I think it's pretty genius and allows you to create your own tasting menu. We choose a great bottle of Pinot, the Gary Danko signature from Miura upon the recommendation of the Barman/Server and it was incredible. This bottle of wine was perhaps my perfect Pinot, I was blown away. Big fruit, juicy, moderate spice and perfectly balanced. I did notice the wine list was a bit over priced and the decor a little bit dated/cheesy but the food, beverage and service outweighed any question marks or concerns. 5 stars all the way and worth every penny of the splurge.

My (now-ex-and-soon-to-be-reunited-I-hope) boyfriend took me here as a surprise a year and a half ago when I got my dream job. He did it up just like it was the prom: he bought a new outfit, I bought a new outfit, he had a limo pick me up AND he brought a beautiful bouquet of flowers too. Awesome :) The food was just the icing on the cake...but man, what amazing icing! I honestly can't remember what our main course was, but we had the cheese platter (incredible!!), and dessert for me was the trio of creme brulees.Yes, I had 3. No, I didn't finish them all....but boy did I want to!! Props to the wait staff for not laughing at the rather cheap bottle of champagne my boyfriend brought - we ended up saving it for later ;) I can't wait to try his new restaurant that's slated to open in '08 - I hear it'll be a little less expensive, which means we can eat amazing food more often :)

Wow, I don't know how anybody doesn't give this place five stars. This overall, was the best dining experience I've ever had. I think Louis XIV would be pleased with this place if he was still alive. There are like four people waiting on you at all times. Everything is seamless; all your desires are fulfilled without even vocalizing. I never came close to being upset or disappointed with my investment. I'm relatively young compared to most patrons of GD, and I don't think my looks screams aristocrat, but I was treated like royalty from the minute I walked in this restaurant, which happens to be in one of the most beautiful neighborhoods in the world. Gary Danko is more than just an eatery, it is an experience that both tantalizes and satisfies your senses. It has a kind of over-the-top restraint. It gives a permanence to the ephemeral. It's one of those rare occasions, where you're happy to be given the opportunity to spend five-hundred dollars on something that leaves you with only a memory. I could write a poem about it. My girlfriend and I did the 5 course menu with wine pairings. That is the only way to fully experience a place like GD. These places pay good money for sommeliers, so you might as well use them. Eating great food paired with the perfect great wine is probably my favorite thing to do. I honestly think people wouldn't need to do hard drugs if they knew how good that can make you feel. Do yourself a favor and go to this place or a place like it at least once before you die. Unless you don't love great food, great wine, and impeccable service--in that case, save your money and go someplace else.

Great value. A review of my first tasting at the bar. With tons of promotion from a friend, my boyfriend and I decided to head up north, hang out by the Bay and dine at Danko's. However, since it was a last minute thought on a Friday night, availability was non-existent at this restaurant (no walk-ins, reservations recommended). We ended up at the bar with a couple of smokey martinis (my favorite, that's a gin martini with a splash of scotch). Anyhow, in the midst of drinking, we noticed people ordering and eating at the bar. We asked he bartender if he would show us the menu. It was a full-tasting menu with 3, 4, or 5 courses (under a $100, but pairings tip it over). I recommend the options with the formaggio plate. (Wow, that cart and their cheese fridge is to die for! It's up there with the rolling cow from the Inn @ Little Washington.) Nonetheless, after 30 mins, everyone at the bar was doing it, eating that is. (The site was like the last time I went to L'Orangerie in Los Angeles, less than a week before there grand closing reservations were tough to come by. So, people made due at the bar. Luckily, with precognition, I wasn't one of them.) Dining on the countertop was a great affair. You sit there peering at other people's dishes (comparing) and eventually striking conversations with them because you're in such close proximity, something that would rarely happen when you're dining in the main room. The decor reminds me of a Southeast Asian disco-tech from the 80s (black, mirrors, and Ikebana arrangements), very hokie. But, that's okay because what on the plate compensates. The shoe shine in the bathroom probably gets good use, but the soothing water fountain beneath the bathroom sink seemed more out of place than soothing. The second bathroom above the first flight of steps and next to the private room is a little more soothing. The service is superb, even on the bar. My boyfriend and I each received one of those golden take-home numbers and a signed copy of our menu by the chef, without even asking. Wonderful experience!

After two years of waiting, my boyfriend finally took me to Gary Danko for our anniversary. Finally! Of course, this meant I had a lot of high expectations (the standard currently set by Farallon on Post). Things I noticed upon arrival: * Very dim inside. Either my eyes didn't adjust after two hours, or it was too dark. * Waitstaff was attentive, polite, professional (and all male, not that it matters). Their voices can get very high-pitched, though I don't know why that is. And DON'T FILL UP ON BREAD! They are sooo good at keeping your bread plate stocked, but don't feel obligated to eat it! * Bathrooms are super pretty. Need your shoes shined? Stop in here. * The side room to the left is ten times more pleasant than the main room. Less noise from the bar. I got 4 courses from the Summer Menu: Round 1 ~ Corn Soup: My favorite part of the meal from start to finish! The presentation was impeccable. The texture and tastes, unbelievable. Who would ever think a "ham biscuit" would ever be appealing? This was the heaviest part of my meal. Round 2 ~ Seared Seascallops/Roast Maine Lobster: I ordered the seascallops, but ended up stealing my bf's lobster because it was AMAZING! Second favorite of the night. So tender and light in a tomato basil sauce. Plus, I really love corn. Round 3 ~ Loin of Lamb: I don't know how I managed to finish this plate after filling myself up with the first two. I think it was so good I forgot to stop eating. The polenta and veggies were a great balance to the red meat. Round 4 ~ Chocolate Souffle: I'm a chocolate person, so there was no way that anyone was going to talk me out of getting it for dessert. However, it was the biggest disappointment of the night. Not chocolate-y enough! It's like a magic trick; I see them pour chocolate in, but the richness of the chocolate never seems to weigh in my mouth. Too bad. Don't miss out on the Yogurt Panna Cotta, though; it's a GEM easy to overlook. The meal was completed by a plate of cookies, a candle, and a "Happy Anniversary" styled in chocolate on the plate. How sweet of you, Mr. Danko. Oh, and a breakfast pineapple cake for later. This was definitely a fantastic meal. It's not 5 stars because I still think Farallon has GD beat in atmosphere and (just barely) food. However, this place is not one to miss.

First off, I was on the wait list trying to get a reservation for Feb 15. All had seem to be lost when on Friday the 13th of all days, I received a missed call. It was Gary Danko and they said they had a cancellation and it would be first come first served for the reservation. I jumped on the phone like none other and was able to get a seating at 9:30 PM. So my GF and I arrive about an hour early and took a seat at the bar as we waited for our reservation. They have some stunning orchid arrangements all about the restaurant. We were finally seated at 9:29 PM just as my GF had predicted. The one bad thing about where we were seated was that it seemed to be a bit dimmer than the other tables. Made picture taking not so successful. They started us out with a butternut squash soup with some bacon, chives, some vanilla something, and a green sauce as we were looking at the menu. My only gripe with that is usually an amuse buche is a hint of the meal to come. That didn't detract from its deliciousness though. We decided to do 3 courses each. GF: Lobster Risotto: The rice was cooked perfectly. The shrimp were plump and cooked just right as was the lobster. GF didn't like the parsley on it, so I was more than willing to eat it with a bit of risotto accompanying it. Scallops: 2 perfectly seared scallops nestled atop parsnip puree with maitake mushrooms between them. I agreed with the GF when she said that the parsnip puree by itself had a bit of an odd flavor.. But once I took a bit of everything together, the flavors melded quite well. Filet of Beef: T-E-N-D-E-R! Melt in your mouth. GF thought it was a little too rare in the middle for her taste. More for me. Here's what I ordered: White Winter Root Soup with Duck Confit Terrine: I'd have to say that this was one awesome soup. The cold terrine with the warm soup played well together. I can see why people rave about it. Seared Foie Gra: I'd say that there isn't a liver that I don't like. The saying holds true especially for foie. The sweetness of the apples and carmelized onions helped cut the fat from the foie. Not that I'm saying fat is bad, fat is definitely flavor. I usually don't like fruit with my meat, but I can say I'm beginning to be more open to that combination. Bison: I don't remember what the bison took the place of, but once I saw it on the menu, I had to try it. I love trying new types of meat. It came with herb spaetzle and braised cipollini onions. I can say that bison definitely has a distinct flavor from beef. However I enjoyed the new taste of a new meat. Earlier before we ordered, I had requested to move to the table next to us as the seats for that table were both on couch, but the news didn't reach the hostess as another couple was seated there. Our hostess, Susan, felt bad and said we would have something sweet coming out for us since we didn't get to move and because we didn't order dessert. Out came a macaroon ice cream sandwich which was funny since I had made macaroons for the first time a few days before that. The macaroons were pistachio with cream cheese ice cream and a berry sauce. It was a nice small treat. Then out came the usually little tray of mini desserts. I was definitely full by then especially since we had gotten a sundae at Ghirardeli before dinner as the GF was hungry. None of the desserts were really that fantastic. I was a little disappointed as I had told GD that it was our anniversary, but nothing was mentioned by the staff. Then out came the surprise of another dessert by our hostess. It had Happy Anniversary written in chocolate on the plate in very nice writing on the plate. There was a citrusy panna cotta type dessert with a candle in it. We were desserted, but luckily this was more tart than sweet. When we left, our hostess gave the GF a chocolate cream cheese cake and as we were about to leave out the door, our hostess gave a rose and a small box of chocolates to the GF. Needless to say, the GF was quite happy. The staff at GD are top notch and a pleasure to have been served by. As was the food. Definitely worth the Michelin Star. I would definitely return here again.

Dined here last night as my first upscale dining experience for my birthday/graduation. The service was wonderful and the first server was quite giddy at the fact that my friend and I were both first time diners. Before we sat down, there was a bit of a wait despite our reservations, so we sat at the bar. The sauvignon blanc I had was nice and light with a sweet finish, exactly the type of wine I like and I regret not paying closer attention to what label it was. While we were perusing the menu, we received a tasting of a soup, which if I recall correctly, was a duck breast in a coconut curry tasting soup (kind of like thai curry) with drops of chili oil. For dinner, I ordered the 5 courses, tripling up on appetizers, one seafood dish, and a meat dish. Yes, I'm a little piggy. I was eyeing the creme brulee for dessert, but I couldn't make up my mind as to the appetizers so my friend kindly ordered the creme brulee for his fifth course. :-D I ordered (1) the Glazed Oysters with Osetra Caviar, Zucchini Pearls and Lettuce Cream, (2) the Risotto with Lobster, Rock Shrimp, Asparagus, Morel Mushrooms and Stinging Nettles, (3) the Seared Sonoma Foie Gras with Caramelized Red Onions and Rhubarb, (4) Mushroom Dusted Sea Scallops with English Pea Purée, Shimeji Mushrooms and Meyer Lemon, and (5) the Roasted Loin of Bison with King Trumpet Mushrooms, Glazed Cipollini Onions and Herb Spätzle. (Copied and pasted from the menu online.) My friend also ordered the wine pairings for both of us. My server told me he would rearrange the orders for my appetizers so that I would get the most out of them. Is it odd that for some dishes, I enjoyed the accompaniments more than the main food of the dish? Not that the main was bad, just that the garnishing sides were uber yummy too! First, I had the foie gras. Never had that before and the texture surprised me. I guess I'd always expected something closer to a liverwurst texture or something a little chewier? Instead, it was definitely a more smooth buttery texture, kind of like the fat that you find in catfish (yum! I might be the only one who finds that delicious though). It was seared on both sides, so the outside had that tad bit thicker texture than the inside. The accompanying caramelized red onion was sooooooooooooooo yummy, I could have eaten a bowl of that by itself. The wine pairing that came with that was to my liking as well, a little sweet, almost like a dessert wine in my opinion. Second, I got my order of oysters. While it was good, I was disappointed to find a bit of grit on a couple of my oysters. The caviar was good, but I think was expecting a bit more saltiness. The wine I received was pretty good, although it was odd because my friend had the oysters for his first course and he received a different wine which was a little less sweet. Catering to the male palate perhaps? My third appetizer was the risotto (the first appetizer you receive will have bigger portions than the second and third, if you order multiple appetizers like I did). The main reason I ordered this was because of all the damned Hell's Kitchen episodes I've been watching on hulu these past few months. Otherwise, I think I might have gone for one of the salads. Anyhow, while it was good, I don't know if it's something I would crave again. But the portion I received was definitely heartier than that of the foie gras and the oysters (wonder what the portion would have looked like if it had been the main course). Oh, and another thing, because I ordered three appetizers, they ended up staggering my friend's courses, which meant he had to sit without a course in front of him while I finished my second and third courses. I thought that was just really strange and could be quite annoying if you're hungry. My fourth was the dusted scallops, or scallop, in my case. My friend received two, while I got one, probably because my greedy ass had already ordered three appetizers. The scallop was cooked perfectly and was delicious. I love scallops and this one was definitely better than the ones at One Market, which had been the best I'd had up until that point. My fifth, and last, course was the bison. It was good, a little more chewy than beef, and other than that, I can't remember much else about the bison. But oohh, the Cipollini onions were so yummy! (What was up with me and onions that night?) If my friend hadn't been eating his, I totally would have stolen his. As for the spatzle, I wasn't as big on that, although my friend really liked it. To me, it tasted like the texture of the green Vietnamese desserts, minus the sugar and the coconut milk that you can pour in. Since I had opted out of the cheese offering and the dessert, the space in front of me was empty while it was my friend's turn to finish his courses. Of course, he shared those with me so I got to taste the cheeses and brulees as well. Omg. Yelp says I'm out of space to write!

Your San Francisco dining career is incomplete without Gary Danko. I have no idea how it was prepared--it was a panko crusted deep fried egg, but yet like a perfectly cooked poached egg inside.... It was divine. Not sure it needed polenta but it was good.

    Third course: pork belly woth pork tenderloin with a fava bean purée. The pork belly had a maple glaze and was cooked perfectly. The tenderloin was excellent. It was a hearty portion.  I couldnt finish the course because i was already full and still had dessert coming.

    One of my friends had the cheese plate and the presentation made me wish I did as well. It was wheeled out on a cart and the selection was amazing.  One thing we all noted though is that the accoutrements for the cheese plate were not as impressive as the selection of cheeses. I had hoped for some higher end accompanying items instead of just some plain walnuts, some slices of baguette and some grapes.

    Finally dessert.  I had the butter cake, which was really tasty, but it kind of reminded me of a sticky bun.  So a little puzzling since i was expecting more of a pound cake type dessert.  

    we were seated at a table where it seemed to be in some poor accoustics.  I had a difficult time hearing my other dining companions.  

    It is definitely a special occasion place, but some people were dressed like they were just walking in off the street on a whim.  Come on people, you have to call in for a res like two months in advance, leave your t-shirt and jeans at home!

    Couple of cool random things as a female: If you get a little chilly, they have complementary pashminas you can use during the meal.  Also, they have Gary Danko branded handbag hangers for you to hang your bag at the table.  FUN!

    I'd come back again, and the price was much more reasonable than I had imagined.

    11/5/2007

    Tracey and I got there at 6:30 so we could "walk in" and sit at the bar and it was already 3/4's of the way full.  Within 10 minutes the bar was full and dining at the bar is not a quick meal nor do they rush the meal.
    They take reservations 2 months in advance from online, but I'm told there are sometimes cancellations so it's worth trying to put your name on the list.

    I started this amazing night, my first visit to Gary Danko with one of the best Manhattan's ever.  Basil Hayden is always great and one of my favorites, but when the bartender knows how to make a great Manhattan it's golden.  I'm picky about my drinks and truth be told, I generally do not order a Manhattan from a bartender that is under 40 years old.   The drink was highly memorable and a great way to begin a very nice night.

    The way Gary Danko sets up his menu is very interesting and worth investigating more, very soon, I hope.    One can go the 5 course prix fix route or the menu is filled with appetizer as well as entree sized portions, priced accordingly.  You choose 3, 4, 5 course meal options built around your entree choice which can include soup, salad, small plate(s), dessert, cheese.  Your third option or you can just dine normally and order what you want from the menu.  I think it's pretty genius and allows you to create your own tasting menu.

    We choose a great bottle of Pinot, the Gary Danko signature from Miura upon the recommendation of the Barman/Server and it was incredible.  This bottle of wine was perhaps my perfect Pinot, I was blown away.  Big fruit, juicy, moderate spice and perfectly balanced.  I did notice the wine list was a bit over priced and the decor a little bit dated/cheesy but the food, beverage and service outweighed any question marks or concerns.  

    5 stars all the way and worth every penny of the splurge.

    Wow, I don't know how anybody doesn't give this place five stars. This overall, was the best dining experience I've ever had. I think Louis XIV would be pleased with this place if he was still alive. There are like four people waiting on you at all times. Everything is seamless; all your desires are fulfilled without even vocalizing. I never came close to being upset or disappointed with my investment.

    I'm relatively young compared to most patrons of GD, and I don't think my looks screams aristocrat, but I was treated like royalty from the minute I walked in this restaurant, which happens to be in one of the most beautiful neighborhoods in the world.

    Gary Danko is more than just an eatery, it is an experience that both tantalizes and satisfies your senses. It has a kind of over-the-top restraint. It gives a permanence to the ephemeral. It's one of those rare occasions, where you're happy to be given the opportunity to spend five-hundred dollars on something that leaves you with only a memory. I could write a poem about it.

    My girlfriend and I did the 5 course menu with wine pairings. That is the only way to fully experience a place like GD. These places pay good money for sommeliers, so you might as well use them. Eating great food paired with the perfect great wine is probably my favorite thing to do. I honestly think people wouldn't need to do hard drugs if they knew how good that can make you feel.

    Do yourself a favor and go to this place or a place like it at least once before you die. Unless you don't love great food, great wine, and impeccable service--in that case, save your money and go someplace else.

    Great value.

    A review of my first tasting at the bar.

    With tons of promotion from a friend, my boyfriend and I decided to head up north, hang out by the Bay and dine at Danko's.  However, since it was a last minute thought on a Friday night, availability was non-existent at this restaurant (no walk-ins, reservations recommended).  We ended up at the bar with a couple of smokey martinis (my favorite, that's a gin martini with a splash of scotch).  

    Anyhow, in the midst of drinking, we noticed people ordering and eating at the bar.  We asked he bartender if he would show us the menu.  It was a full-tasting menu with 3, 4, or 5 courses (under a $100, but pairings tip it over).  I recommend the options with the formaggio plate.  (Wow, that cart and their cheese fridge is to die for!  It's up there with the rolling cow from the Inn @ Little Washington.)  Nonetheless, after 30 mins, everyone at the bar was doing it, eating that is.  (The site was like the last time I went to L'Orangerie in Los Angeles, less than a week before there grand closing reservations were tough to come by.  So, people made due at the bar.  Luckily, with precognition, I wasn't one of them.)

    Dining on the countertop was a great affair.  You sit there peering at other people's dishes (comparing) and eventually striking conversations with them because you're in such close proximity, something that would rarely happen when you're dining in the main room.

    The decor reminds me of a Southeast Asian disco-tech from the 80s (black, mirrors, and Ikebana arrangements), very hokie.  But,  that's okay because what on the plate compensates.  The shoe shine in the bathroom probably gets good use, but the soothing water fountain beneath the bathroom sink seemed more out of place than soothing.  The second bathroom above the first flight of steps and next to the private room is a little more soothing.

    The service is superb, even on the bar.  My boyfriend and I each received one of those golden take-home numbers and a signed copy of our menu by the chef, without even asking.  Wonderful experience!

    After two years of waiting, my boyfriend finally took me to Gary Danko for our anniversary.  Finally!  Of course, this meant I had a lot of high expectations (the standard currently set by Farallon on Post).  

    Things I noticed upon arrival:
    * Very dim inside.  Either my eyes didn't adjust after two hours, or it was too dark.
    * Waitstaff was attentive, polite, professional (and all male, not that it matters).  Their voices can get very high-pitched, though I don't know why that is.  And DON'T FILL UP ON BREAD!  They are sooo good at keeping your bread plate stocked, but don't feel obligated to eat it!
    * Bathrooms are super pretty.  Need your shoes shined?  Stop in here.
    * The side room to the left is ten times more pleasant than the main room.  Less noise from the bar.

    I got 4 courses from the Summer Menu:
    Round 1 ~ Corn Soup:  My favorite part of the meal from start to finish!  The presentation was impeccable.  The texture and tastes, unbelievable.  Who would ever think a "ham biscuit" would ever be appealing?  This was the heaviest part of my meal.

    Round 2 ~ Seared Seascallops/Roast Maine Lobster:  I ordered the seascallops, but ended up stealing my bf's lobster because it was AMAZING!  Second favorite of the night.  So tender and light in a tomato basil sauce.  Plus, I really love corn.

    Round 3 ~ Loin of Lamb:  I don't know how I managed to finish this plate after filling myself up with the first two.  I think it was so good I forgot to stop eating.  The polenta and veggies were a great balance to the red meat.

    Round 4 ~ Chocolate Souffle:  I'm a chocolate person, so there was no way that anyone was going to talk me out of getting it for dessert.  However, it was the biggest disappointment of the night.  Not chocolate-y enough!  It's like a magic trick; I see them pour chocolate in, but the richness of the chocolate never seems to weigh in my mouth.  Too bad.  Don't miss out on the Yogurt Panna Cotta, though; it's a GEM easy to overlook.

    The meal was completed by a plate of cookies, a candle, and a "Happy Anniversary" styled in chocolate on the plate.  How sweet of you, Mr. Danko.  Oh, and a breakfast pineapple cake for later.  

    This was definitely a fantastic meal.  It's not 5 stars because I still think Farallon has GD beat in atmosphere and (just barely) food.  However, this place is not one to miss.

I was eyeing the creme brulee for dessert, but I couldn't make up my mind as to the appetizers so my friend kindly ordered the creme brulee for his fifth course. :-D  I ordered (1) the Glazed Oysters with Osetra Caviar, Zucchini Pearls and Lettuce Cream, (2) the Risotto with Lobster, Rock Shrimp, Asparagus, Morel Mushrooms and Stinging Nettles, (3) the Seared Sonoma Foie Gras with Caramelized Red Onions and Rhubarb, (4) Mushroom Dusted Sea Scallops with English Pea Purée, Shimeji Mushrooms and Meyer Lemon, and (5) the Roasted Loin of Bison with King Trumpet Mushrooms, Glazed Cipollini Onions and Herb Spätzle. (Copied and pasted from the menu online.)  My friend also ordered the wine pairings for both of us.

    Is it odd that for some dishes, I enjoyed the accompaniments more than the main food of the dish? Not that the main was bad, just that the garnishing sides were uber yummy too!

It was seared on both sides, so the outside had that tad bit thicker texture than the inside.  The accompanying caramelized red onion was sooooooooooooooo yummy, I could have eaten a bowl of that by itself.  The wine pairing that came with that was to my liking as well, a little sweet, almost like a dessert wine in my opinion.

    Second, I got my order of oysters. While it was good, I was disappointed to find a bit of grit on a couple of my oysters. The caviar was good, but I think was expecting a bit more saltiness.  The wine I received was pretty good, although it was odd because my friend had the oysters for his first course and he received a different wine which was a little less sweet. Catering to the male palate perhaps?

    My third appetizer was the risotto (the first appetizer you receive will have bigger portions than the second and third, if you order multiple appetizers like I did).  The main reason I ordered this was because of all the damned Hell's Kitchen episodes I've been watching on hulu these past few months.  Otherwise, I think I might have gone for one of the salads.  Anyhow, while it was good, I don't know if it's something I would crave again.  But the portion I received was definitely heartier than that of the foie gras and the oysters (wonder what the portion would have looked like if it had been the main course).

    Don't skip the cheese cart, we opted to split the cheese and share a desert and were plenty satisfied. The "cheese cart man" gave us a run-down on the thirteen cheeses from every corner of the world and helped find ones that we would enjoy. I can honestly say they were four of the best cheeses I've ever tasted.

    For a special occasion Gary Danko will be hard to beat. If you're ordering from the wine list (book) you might spend a fortune...but $7 Lagunitas IPA's treated me just dandy!

    7/26/2008

    Your San Francisco dining career is incomplete without Gary Danko.

    Gary Danko is restaurant mastery: the food does things to your taste buds that nearly make you feel embarrassed to be in public, the service is friendly, helpful and surprisingly unpretentious.  

    With all the accolades this place has received, I was worried it was going to take itself too seriously.  Nothing ruins my appetite like being condescended to by a waiter.  To my happy surprise, that was not the case at all.  Everyone at Gary Danko was friendly and inviting.

    It's a perfect occasion restaurant, perfect for birthdays and anniversaries but it's also a great way to make any random day of the week into an occasion.

    It's pricy for sure, but completely worth it.  Every course has something amazing to offer -- don't skip any of them.

    10/4/2008

    As good as they say it is. Significant other brought me here for my birthday and it was a nearly transcendent experience.

    First off, the service. Top notch, they are all dressed in suits and all have fairly memorized the menu and can tell you about any dish in detail. If anything, it was maybe a little on the overwhelming side, as we had 3 people come up to us in the space of 5 minutes and ask whether we wanted our wine now, with our bread or with our food and we needed to repeat ourselves.

    Then, the food. Both of us got a 5-course tasting menu so we could try everything. If we did it over again, we probably would have gone with 4 courses each. Even though they customize portion sizes depending on how many courses you get, we were both full for the next week after this dinner.

    The highlights: sweet corn soup. Comes out with kernels of corn, a small biscuit and a few pieces of dungeness crab in the bottom of a bowl and they pour the soup over it all. Refreshing, smooth, just the right amount of sweet.

    Foie gras. We ended up both getting this because we knew we wouldn't want to share. And we were right: absolute happiness in the mouth.

    Cheese plate: We were almost too full at this point to enjoy properly, but still - an amazing selection - I recommend the soft, aromatic cheese from Tasmania.

    Gary Dank is one of those places that a foodie in SF has to try even if it's gonna cost her a couple hundred bucks for dinner.  They offer prix fixe menus based on the number of courses you get but you can order anything you want off the menu for each course.  I had the foie gras, bison, cheeses, and chocolate souffle, all of which were excellent.  I have allergies to raw pitted fruits and the chef was very accommodating.

    Fine dining like no other!!  We came here for my bf's birthday-party of 7.  We made reservations two months in advance and good thing we did because I think that's the only thing to do at this place.  

    Service: spectacular!! best service ever.  I was in awe every second.  Sometimes we would make someone leave for the bathroom to see how quick the staff is and once someone left from the table, they were quick to fold the napkin neatly for us again.

    The place is small so its very intimate.  Lights were dim. Guests were dressed nice and so were we! The guys were looking fly and the girls were stunning.

    I do have to say that everything here was worth every cent spent and honestly, I thought the prices were good for fine dining.  There were 7 of us and the tab came out less than $800 (not including tip and needless to say, we brought in our own wine).  Everyone either did the 3 or 4 course meal.  One friend did the 5 because she wanted to indulge into the desserts, but by the time we all got to our second dish, we were all pretty stuffed.  Since its fine dining, we all ate slow and they do say, the slower you eat, the fuller you get.  By the time we were done, we were ready to nap.

    It was a wonderful experience and I can't wait to go back.  Hopefully the bf will take me back one day.

    PS:  The risotto was to die for!!
